globalization working conditions and labor rights implications for developing countries siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display globalization working conditions and labor rights implications for developing countries type scid working paper 345 author s robert flanagan published 05 1 07 region general download pdf abstract evidence from a broad sample of industrialized and developing countries is used to examine the links between globalization and labor conditions and to formulate implications for india and other developing countries cross country instrumental variable analysis demonstrates that no direct link between openness and working conditions exists trade liberalization improves working conditions indirectly by raising per capita income empirical analyses also show the adoption of a free trade policy is associated with lower child labor rates and greater civil liberties ordinary least squares and instrumental variable estimates find significantly larger male female wage differences in countries with open trade polices ceteris paribus underlying reasons for this result are unclear and data used in the analysis are not ideal though the role of international labor standards may be limited target policies that expand the opportunities of specific groups in india and other developing countries merit serious consideration it is these policies rather than restrictions on globalization that hold the potential to improve labor conditions around the world stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
